{{refimprove|date=May 2010}} '''Dysteleology''' is the [[philosophy|philosophical]] view that [[existence]] has no ''[[telos (philosophy)|telos]]'' - no [[Four causes|final cause]] from purposeful [[design]]. [[Ernst Haeckel]] (1834-1919) invented and popularized the word "dysteleology"<ref> {{cite journal|title= Natural Selection and Dysteleology|author= [[George Romanes|Romanes, George J.]]|journal= Nature|volume= 9|pages= 361–2|date= 1874-03-12|doi= 10.1038/009361a0 |issue= 228 | quote = 'Prof. Haeckel has invented a new and convenient name, "Dysteleology," for the study of the "purposelessnesses" which are observable in living organisms—such as the multitudinous cases of rudimentary and apparently useless structures.'}} </ref> ({{lang-de | Dysteleologie}}<ref> {{Cite OED1 | dysteleology }} </ref>). Dysteleology is an aggressive, yet optimistic, form of science-oriented [[atheism]]{{cn|date=October 2018}} originally perhaps{{or|date=October 2018}} associated with Haeckel and his followers, but now perhaps more associated{{by whom?|date=October 2018}} with the type of atheism of [[Richard Dawkins]], [[Sam Harris (author)|Sam Harris]], or [[Christopher Hitchens]]. Transcending traditional philosophical and religious perspectives, such as [[German idealism]] (including the philosophies of [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]] and [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]]) and contemporary [[New Age]] thinking, [[Modernism|modern]] [[philosophical naturalism]] sees existence as having no inherent goal.{{cn|date=January 2017}}
