The '''Holy Confucian Church''' or '''Holy Church of Confucius''' (孔圣会 ''Kǒngshènghuì'') or '''Holy Confucian Church of China''' (中华孔圣会 ''Zhōnghuá Kǒngshènghuì'') is a body formed of many local [[Confucian churches]] or halls (孔圣堂 ''Kǒngshèngtáng'') in [[China]]. The [[grassroots]] movement was initiated by Zhou Beichen, a disciple of the Confucian philosopher [[Jiang Qing (Confucian)|Jiang Qing]], who founded the first holy church in [[Shenzhen]] in 2009.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=152-154}} The aim of the movement was to develop a network of local Confucian churches throughout the country,{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=156}} eventually unifying into a national body and becoming the [[state religion]] of China.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=156}} The Holy Confucian Church has received support from the [[Confucian Academy]] of [[Hong Kong]], although it has developed independently from the latter.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=152}}

In 2010 the first holy church in Shenzhen was officially registered as a non-governmental non-profit (''fēi qǐyè'' 非企业) organisation of public interest (''gōngyì'' 公益) affiliated with the Federation of Confucian Culture of [[Qufu]] City.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=154}} The Holy Church maintains close relations with local government officials and high-ranking dignitaries of the [[State Administration for Religious Affairs]] attend its ceremonies.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=155}} The national and international body, the Holy Confucian Church of China, was finally established in late 2015.<ref name="Hou">{{cite article|last=Hou|first=Xiaobing|title=当代儒家成立“孔圣会”意欲何为？|trans-title=Contemporary Ruists set up "Holy Church of Confucius", what will this mean?|publisher=China Confucian Philosophy Network|date=13 November 2015|url=http://www.rujiazg.com/article/id/6921/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117155316/http://www.rujiazg.com/article/id/6921/|archive-date=17 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite article|title=深圳成立「中華孔聖會」 面向全球弘揚儒道|trans-title=Holy Confucian Church of China set up in Shenzhen for the worldwide promotion of the Ruist way|website=gd.wenweipo.com|date=26 November 2015|url=http://gd.wenweipo.com/?action-viewnews-itemid-13082|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406235633/http://gd.wenweipo.com/?action-viewnews-itemid-13082|archive-date=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="Zhang Bo">{{cite article|last=Zhang|first=Bo|title=中华孔圣会”成立 儒家拟走向宗教化|trans-title=Holy Confucian Church established to be the hub of Confucian religion|website=news.sohu.com|date=20 November 2015|url=http://news.sohu.com/20151120/n427407420.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213190347/http://news.sohu.com/20151120/n427407420.shtml|archive-date=13 February 2017}}</ref>

==History of the founder and the organisation==
Zhou Beichen was born in the province of [[Guizhou]] in 1965.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=153}} He studies at the [[Guizhou University]] and experienced with work in journalism, publishing and teaching.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=153}} In the 1980s he was interested in [[Western philosophy]], while in the 1990s he studied the works of many contemporary [[Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucian]] circles.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=153}}

Later, Zhou Beichen approached to [[Jiang Qing (Confucian)|Jiang Qing]]'s work on the [[Gongyang Zhuan|Gongyang]] (公羊) school of [[New Text Confucianism]], especially the idea of political Confucianism or the "outside kingship" (外王).{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=153}} In 1996 he met Jiang Qing in person and they founded together the Yangming Academy in Guizhou.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=153}} Between that year and 2003 he settled down in [[Shenzhen]], living with business activity and projecting the Confucian holy halls (''Kongshengtang'') movement which officially started in 2009.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=153}}

The Confucian holy halls multiplied over the following years and on 1 November 2015 many Confucian scholars including Jiang Qing, Kang Xiaoguang, Zhang Xianglong and Sheng Hong gathered in Shenzhen for the formal establishment of a national and international Holy Confucian Church which would encompass all local Confucian congregations and civil organisations.<ref name="Hou"/> Jiang Qing was appointed as the spiritual leader of the church.<ref name="Hou"/>

Some see the Holy Confucian Church as a continuation of the Confucian Church that was founded in 1912 by [[Kang Youwei]], a Confucian reformer, but which was later disbanded because of hostile political climate.<ref name="Hou"/> The contemporary Holy Confucian Church aims to foster folk Confucian and traditional religion in a period of deep crisis of the Chinese civilisation, and represent a "body" for the "soul" of the Chinese, or a new embodiment of the "wandering soul" of Confucianism deprived of its social structure after the empire fell apart.<ref name="Zhang Bo"/> The church has found some opposition, even within the Confucian community, by people who see it as an imitation of [[Christianity]] and fear a departure from the teachings of Confucianism.<ref name="Hou"/>

Besides the nourishment of Chinese culture, the Holy Church's constitution also mentions the aim of maintaining the "religious ecology" (宗教生态 ''zōngjiào shēngtài'') of Chinese society through the absorption and reinterpretation of alien religions and heterodox cults into Confucianism.<ref name="Hou"/>

==Structure of the church==
The Holy Confucian Church is a highly structured institution both in its doctrine of the faith and in its organisation.<ref name="Zhang Bo"/> The reference to its "holiness" in its name means that the church reflects the sacred order of nature in holidays, ancestral ties and the environment.<ref name="Zhang Bo"/>

Its local congregations (孔圣堂 ''Kǒngshèngtáng'') are at the same times schools and temples (学庙和一 ''xué miào hé yī'') for the education of the individuals and the moral reconstitution of society, the filial way (孝慈之道 ''xiàocí zhī dào'') and spiritual home (精神家园 ''jīngshén jiāyuán'') of Chinese life.{{sfnb|Payette|2014}} Its worship halls are called ''dàochǎng'' (道场 "place of the way"), a term for wide worship halls.

==Economy of the church==
In order to develop independently from the support of sponsors as it was the case in the first months after its creation, in 2010 the Holy Confucian Church of Shenzhen adopted a "sustainable development model", also termed the "Shenzhen model" by the media.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=155}} The policy implies the self-support of the Church through wedding and funeral rites, and through schools of "Confucian corporate culture" for business companies.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=155}} The goal of the church is to provide non-profit services, and it offers education, rituals and other activities which are free of charge.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|p=155}}

The nationwide Holy Confucian Church created in 2015 plans to replicate the Shenzhen model all over China and abroad and form missionary institutes and community-oriented lecture circuits, and Confucian schools.<ref name="Zhang Bo"/> These objectives will be financed by integrated social donations and funding members, contributions from local government for public services at [[Temples of Confucius]], its industrial platform, and other resources.<ref name="Zhang Bo"/>

